class Graph(): 
  
    def __init__(self, vertices): 
        self.vertices = vertices 
        self.graph = [[0 for column in range(vertices)] for row in range(vertices)] 
  
    # prints out the minimum spanning tree with edge and weight
    def print_MST(self, mst): 
        print("Edge \tWeight")
        for i in range(1, self.vertices): 
            print(mst[i], "-", i, "\t", self.graph[i][mst[i]] )
  
    # Selects the edge that has the minimum weight
    def min_vertex(self, vset, visited): 
        min = sys.maxsize
        for v in range(self.vertices): 
            if vset[v] < min and visited[v] == False: 
                min = vset[v] 
                min_index = v 
        return min_index 
  
    # Constructs a minimum spanning tree from the graph
    def find_MST(self): 
  
        # keeps track of the weights of the min path
        # initialized with maximum numbers
        vset = [sys.maxsize] * self.vertices
        # picks the root vertex as the first one
        vset[0] = 0 
        # stores the minimum spanning tree
        mst = [None] * self.vertices
        mst[0] = -1
        # keeps track of which nodes have been visited
        visited = [False] * self.vertices
        # graph from networkx is created to make plotting easier
        G = nx.Graph()
  
        for vertex in range(self.vertices): 
  
            # Get the smallest weight path 
            u = self.min_vertex(vset, visited) 
  
            # Mark the vertex as visited 
            visited[u] = True
  
            for v in range(self.vertices): 
                # go through all the vertices that haven't been visited
                # if index in vset is greater than the graph edge (not a minimum)
                # update the distance in vset (shortest path weights) and mst (minimum spanning tree)
                if self.graph[u][v] > 0 and visited[v] == False and vset[v] > self.graph[u][v]: 
                        vset[v] = self.graph[u][v] 
                        mst[v] = u 
                        G.add_edge(v, u)
        return mst, sum(vset), G

In the graph shown above, all edges of the graph have an equal weight. Thus, when starting from the root node, an arbitrary edge is removed from the graph, since there is no real "minimum" edge. This means that the graph can possibly have another minimum spanning tree.

Problem 1d¶

The algorithm in part A is only deterministic if all edge weights are different. Otherwise, another minimum spanning tree may be possible, since when choosing the edge with the lowest weight, these results may be ambiguous. One way to expand this to return all MSTs would be to keep track of two different edges if the min edge weight is the same between multiple edges.

Problem 2a¶

Write an algorithm that implements Louvain clustering on a graph by partitioning it into a set of communities.

In [423]:
# naive implementation
def modularity(G, c): 
    A = nx.adjacency_matrix(G).todense()
    m = 0.5 * np.sum(A)
    summa = 0
    for i in range(len(A)): 
        for j in range(len(np.asarray(A)[0])): 
            # degrees of vertex are equal to row sum in adjacency matrix
            # no weights on edges
            ki = np.sum(A[i])
            kj = np.sum(A[j])
            # if communities are not equal
            if c[i] != c[j]:
                d = 0
            else: 
                d = 1
            # update the summation
            summa += (np.asarray(A)[i][j] - (ki*kj)/(2*m)) * d
    return (1/(2*m)) * summa

# gets the constant term in the algorithm
def get_const_mtx(G): 
    A = nx.adjacency_matrix(G).todense()
    m = 0.5 * np.sum(A)
    mtx = np.zeros((A.shape))
    for i in range(len(A)): 
        for j in range(len(np.asarray(A)[0])): 
            # degrees of vertex are equal to row sum in adjacency matrix
            # no weights on edges
            ki = np.sum(A[i])
            kj = np.sum(A[j])
            # update the matrix
            mtx[i][j] = (np.asarray(A)[i][j] - (ki*kj)/(2*m))
    return mtx

# optimized modularity function
def modularity_opt(G, c, const): 
    A = nx.adjacency_matrix(G).todense()
    m = 0.5 * np.sum(A)
    x, y = np.indices(A.shape)
    comm = np.asarray(c)
    boolarr = np.where(comm[x] == comm[y], 1, 0)
    return np.sum(const * boolarr)

# louvain clustering algorithm
def louvain_cluster(G): 
    c = [i for i in G.nodes]
    const = get_const_mtx(G)
    orig_mod = modularity_opt(G, c, const)
    prev_mod = 0
    while True: 
        for node in G.nodes: 
            neighbors_ = G.neighbors(node)
            max_neighbor_mod = -1*sys.maxsize
            best_neighbor_c = c.copy()
            for n in neighbors_: 
                tmp = c.copy()
                # set the community to the neighbor's
                tmp[node] = n
                curr_mod = modularity_opt(G, tmp, const)
                if curr_mod > max_neighbor_mod: 
                    max_neighbor_mod = curr_mod
                    best_neighbor_c = tmp.copy()
            # iterated through all neighbors
            # see if the modularity can increase by moving communities
            if max_neighbor_mod > orig_mod: 
                c = best_neighbor_c.copy()
                orig_mod = max_neighbor_mod
        if abs(prev_mod - orig_mod) < 0.000001: 
            break
        prev_mod = orig_mod
    return c

# points in each dataset -> 30 total points
def two_multivariate_distros(points, m1, m2, cov1, cov2): 
    x0 = np.random.multivariate_normal(m1, cov1, (1, 1, points))[0][0]
    x1 = np.random.multivariate_normal(m2, cov2, (1, 1, points))[0][0]
    dataset = np.concatenate((x0, x1))
    return x0, x1, dataset

def generate_knn_graph(dataset, nk): 
    # create a array of distances between one point in the dataset and the rest of the points
    d = [euclidean_distances(dataset, [dataset[i]]) for i in range(len(dataset))]
    # process the data so it can be used later
    data = []
    for lst in d: 
        data.append(lst.flatten())
    # sort the data from nearest -> farthest by argument
    sort = np.argsort(data)
    # 3set the number of neighbors
    k = nk
    # create a graph and add nodes (# of points in dataset)
    G = nx.Graph()
    G.add_nodes_from(range(len(dataset)))
    # build the KNN graph
    for p in range(len(dataset)):
        # exclude the 0th closest neighbor (itself)
        neighbors = sort[p][1:k+1]
        # add an edge to each kth nearest neighbor
        for n in neighbors: 
            G.add_edge(p, n)
    return G

# louvain clustering algorithm
def louvain_cluster_plot(G, state): 
    global Q
    global iterations
    c = [i for i in G.nodes]
    const = get_const_mtx(G)
    orig_mod = modularity_opt(G, c, const)
    prev_mod = 0
    while True: 
        Q[state].append(orig_mod)
        iterations[state] += 1
        for node in G.nodes: 
            neighbors_ = G.neighbors(node)
            max_neighbor_mod = -1*sys.maxsize
            best_neighbor_c = c.copy()
            for n in neighbors_: 
                tmp = c.copy()
                # set the community to the neighbor's
                tmp[node] = n
                curr_mod = modularity_opt(G, tmp, const)
                if curr_mod > max_neighbor_mod: 
                    max_neighbor_mod = curr_mod
                    best_neighbor_c = tmp.copy()
            # iterated through all neighbors
            # see if the modularity can increase by moving communities
            if max_neighbor_mod > orig_mod: 
                c = best_neighbor_c.copy()
                orig_mod = max_neighbor_mod
        if abs(prev_mod - orig_mod) < 0.000001: 
            break
        prev_mod = orig_mod
    return c
